Reasoning: 
1. cs.IT (Information Theory) - The paper deals with the design of codes with linear minimum distance, which is a fundamental concept in information theory. 
2. cs.CC (Computational Complexity) - The paper discusses the decoding complexity and convergence of the proposed code ensemble, which is a key aspect of computational complexity. 
3. cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) - The paper may be relevant to networking and internet architecture as low-rate codes with linear minimum distance are important for reliable communication over noisy channels. 
4. cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) - The paper may be relevant to social and information networks as codes with low decoding complexity and fast convergence are desirable for distributed storage and communication in such networks. 
5. cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) - The paper may be relevant to data structures and algorithms as the proposed code ensemble has a simple structure and satisfies a necessary condition on the linear minimum distance, which may be of interest to researchers working on algorithmic design of codes.
